  <div class="grid-container">
    <div class="grid-item">
      <section id="intro">
        <h2>Overview</h2>
        <p>
          
Frederick Douglass, a towering figure in the 19th-century abolitionist 
movement, is primarily celebrated for his impassioned abolitionist activism, 
mesmerizing oratorical prowess, and influential roles in the realm of 
literature and journalism. As a fervent advocate for the immediate 
emancipation of slaves, Douglass's compelling speeches, notably 
encapsulated in his autobiographical work "Narrative of the Life of Frederick 
Douglass," brought to light the brutal realities of slavery and played a 
pivotal role in galvanizing support for the anti-slavery cause.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <div class="grid-item">
      <section id="achievements">
        <h2>Achievements</h2>
        1. <strong>Autobiography: "Narrative of the Life"</strong>
   <ul>
       <li>Published 1845</li>
       <li>Revealed harsh realities of slavery</li>
       <li>Influential in abolitionist movement</li>
       <li>Showcased Douglass's literary prowess</li>
   </ul>

2. <strong>Advisor to President Lincoln:</strong>
   <ul>
       <li>Civil War collaboration</li>
       <li>Influenced Emancipation Proclamation</li>
       <li>Critical discussions on slavery</li>
       <li>Impact on African American enlistment</li>
   </ul>

3. <strong>Women's Suffrage Advocate:</strong>
   <ul>
       <li>Seneca Falls Convention participant</li>
       <li>Endorsed Declaration of Sentiments</li>
       <li>Supported by prominent suffragists</li>
       <li>Recognized interconnected struggles for equality</li>
   </ul>
      </section>
    </div>

    <div class="grid-item">
      <section id="legacy">
        <h2>Legacy</h2>
      <p>
          <strong> Literary Legacy:</strong>
          Frederick Douglass's literary impact endures, with his eloquent prose in the "Narrative" influencing the discourse on human rights and equality. His writings, a catalyst for abolitionism, continue to be studied for their historical significance in shaping conversations about race, freedom, and justice.
      </p>
      
      <p>
          <strong> Inspiration for Future Generations:</strong>
          Frederick Douglass's life story is a perennial source of inspiration, underscoring human resilience and the ability to effect positive change. From enslavement to statesmanship, Douglass's legacy serves as a beacon for those in the ongoing struggle for civil rights and social justice, encouraging courage, advocacy against injustice, and the pursuit of a more equitable world.
      </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </div>

